<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-13-1004 </DOCNO><TEXT>This paper is aimed mainly at providing pediatricians with informationabout the practical aspects of magnetic resonance imaging and introducingthem to the new terms used in this technique without however going intothe intricacies of magnetic resonance. Magnetic resonance imaging isprimarily indicated for studying soft tissues, the central nervous system,soft parts in general and specifically the ''envelope'' of the bonesand joints, and the cardiovascular system. Selected images illustratingthe results for most organs easily show and demonstrate the technique'sadvantages, and draw attention to the value of the anatomic or even pathologicrepresentation of anomalies in all the different planes. No ionizingradiations are delivered. The main drawbacks are the length and costof studies.</TEXT></DOC>